  "text": "Traditional microbial culture techniques have demonstrated that approximately 50% of COPD exacerbations are associated with pathogens such as Streptococcus pneumoniae, Haemophilus influenzae, and Moraxella catarrhalis. These organisms can often be found colonizing the airways of COPD patients between exacerbations [CITATION_1] . The term lung microbiome has been used to describe this community of organisms inhabiting the lung. Since many of these bacteria persist in the airways of patients with COPD, their presence may promote a chronic inflammatory state that drives COPD pathogenesis.",
